1

00:00:00,000  -->  00:00:03,720
Now that we've looked at how linear regression works,

2

00:00:03,720  -->  00:00:07,300
let's look at how we can do linear regression in Python.

3

00:00:07,300  -->  00:00:11,960
There are two main libraries that are used to perform linear aggression in Python.

4

00:00:11,960  -->  00:00:14,340
The first is statsmodels,

5

00:00:14,340  -->  00:00:16,240
which we'll use in this lesson.

6

00:00:16,240  -->  00:00:18,715
The second is scikit-learn.

7

00:00:18,715  -->  00:00:23,680
Statsmodels is used in many cases due to the way that it resembles stats

8

00:00:23,680  -->  00:00:26,220
output that you might see in languages more commonly

9

00:00:26,220  -->  00:00:29,460
used by statisticians like R and SAS.

10

00:00:29,460  -->  00:00:35,520
Alternatively, scikit-learn is very popular for lots of machine learning algorithms

11

00:00:35,520  -->  00:00:38,180
because of its ease of making predictions

12

00:00:38,180  -->  00:00:41,825
and quickly fitting many types of models to compare.

13

00:00:41,825  -->  00:00:46,130
Because we are focused not only on creating our linear models in this course,

14

00:00:46,130  -->  00:00:52,170
but also analyzing the coefficients and statistical significance of those coefficients,

15

00:00:52,170  -->  00:00:54,690
we'll be using statsmodels for this course.

16

00:00:54,690  -->  00:00:58,130
On the next page, we'll look at exactly how we might use

17

00:00:58,130  -->  00:01:02,130
statsmodels to fit and analyze a linear model in Python.

18

00:01:02,130  -->  00:01:05,950
We'll write code very similar to the documentation that you see here,

19

00:01:05,950  -->  00:01:08,430
and we'll get output that looks just like this.

20

00:01:08,430  -->  00:01:12,930
Lots of output that we can use to better understand our models.
